Hypothesis Testing


Introduction


Audience: Someone with working knowledge of Python and knows statistical test (such as t-test and chi-square test) and how to run those test in Python, and now interested in learning about conducting power analysis in Python, the type of errors in hypothesis testing and calculating their probabilities.

Prerequisite: Introduction to Python and Statistical Test (in the pre-course information folder)

Description: This is a short course on hypothesis testing, it mainly covers the type of errors while conducting a hypothesis test, calculating the probability of those errors, conducting a power analysis to find the power and sample size of a test. Firstly, the theory will be shown, then an example of how to apply the corresponding theory in python will be shown, and lastly, there will be an exercise for learners to be completed.

2 Hypothesis testing

In hypothesis testing, you are performing statistical test to determine whether you believe a statement to be true or false. One common example of this is whether you believe two populations to be statistically different from one another. There are seven steps to follow when you are using any statistical test:

  1. State the null hypothesis \(H_{0}\) and alternative hypothesis \(H_{a}\)
  2. Decide the significance level, \(\alpha\)
  3. Compute the observed test statistics
  4. Determine the critical value
  5. Determine the p-value
  6. Determine the confidence interval
  7. Interpret your results

These steps are covered in the Statistical_test file in the Pre_course_information folder. In this course, we will run a t-test, see what potential error can occur while conducting hypothesis testing, and finally conduct a power analysis to minimise errors with hypothesis testing.

We will be using the airquality data to find out if the average temperature in May is significantly different from the average temperature in July. So, we will create two data frames that contains all observations in May and July respectively and then select the temperature column from both data sets as shown below:

# Here we are filtering airquality data to get two data frames 
# first consist of observations in May and second consist of observations in July

may = airquality[airquality['month'] == 5]

july = airquality[airquality['month'] == 7]

# Then select the temperature column 

temp_may = may['temp']

temp_july = july['temp']

Then we will construct a two-tailed test where the null hypothesis and alternative hypothesis are shown below:

\(H_{0}:\) Mean temperature in May is the same as the mean temperature in July

\(H_{a}:\) Mean temperature in May is different from the mean temperature in July

Then we will run a t-test as shown below:

# Run two-sided independent t-test where x and y needs to be an array-like or float,
# paired = False means the groups are independent, 
# correction = auto means it will automatically use Welch t-test (variance unequal),
# our alpha is 0.05

t_test_temp = pg.ttest(x=temp_may, y=temp_july, paired=False, 
                  tail='two-sided', correction='auto', confidence=0.95)

# Display the observed statistics
# by specifying the name of the variable 
# or using print() function if you are using spyder

t_test_temp['T']
## T-test   -12.616439
## Name: T, dtype: float64
# Display the p-value 

t_test_temp['p-val']
## T-test    1.580321e-18
## Name: p-val, dtype: float64
# Display the 95% CI

t_test_temp['CI95%']
## T-test    [-21.26, -15.44]
## Name: CI95%, dtype: object

Reminder: If you are using Jupyter Notebook or RStudio then you can print your output by specifying the variable name however if you are using Spyder then you need to use the print() function to print output.

From the output, we can see that the average temperature between May and July is statistically significant at a 5% significance level, as:

  • Critical Value Approach: The t-value is less than \(\pm 2.0003\)
  • P-value Approach: The p-value is less than 0.05
  • Confidence Interval: The 95% confidence interval does not contain 0

Hence, we can reject the null hypothesis at a 5% significance level which suggests that the average difference in temperature between May and July is statistically significant.

If you didn’t understand the output and approaches we took to make this decision, then please look at the Statistical test file in the pre-course information folder.

3 Type I error and Type II error

After conducting a hypothesis test, we decide whether to reject the null hypothesis or not. However, this can never be said with complete certainty as we are working with probabilities. There is always a chance of making an incorrect decision which leads us to two errors:

  • Type I error: is also known as a false positive, and occurs when a researcher incorrectly rejects a null hypothesis when in reality it is true.

  • Type II error: is also known as a false negative, and occurs when a researcher does not reject a null hypothesis when in reality it is false.



Continuing with the airquality example, when we are conducting the following hypothesis:

\(H_{0}:\) Mean temperature in May is the same as the mean temperature in July.

\(H_{a}:\) Mean temperature in May is different from the mean temperature in July.

Then the Type I and II errors are as follows:

  • Type I error (false positive): concluding that there is a difference in mean temperature of both months (rejecting \(H_{0}\)), but in reality, the mean temperature of both months are the same (\(H_{0}\) is true).

  • Type II error (false negative): concluding that the mean temperature of both months are the same (not rejecting \(H_{0}\)), but in reality, there is a difference in the mean temperature of both months (\(H_{0}\) is false).


4 Probability of Type I error

Now we know what type I and type II errors are, but in real life, we are interested in learning about the probabilities of these errors. The probability of making a type I error (also known as type I error rate) is the significance level, denoted as \(\alpha\). We are now going to do some simulations to compute an empirical probability of type I error (type I error rate) and check that it is approximately equal to \(\alpha\), basing the test decisions on the p-values returned by the t-test.

Suppose that \(X_1, X_2,..., X_{20}\) is a random sample where X is the temperature in May and \(X \sim N(\mu,6^2)\). We are interested in testing if the mean temperature in May is greater than 50 degrees Fahrenheit or not.

# Create a variable and name it simulations
# function float will give us the value of p-value from t-test instead of type and value
# then run one-sided t-test where x is a random sample from the normal distribution,
# with mean 50 and the standard deviation is 6 
# and y is just 50 because we want to test if the mean temperature in May is greater than 50
# select p-value from t-test and run this t-test 10000 times

simulations = [float(pg.ttest(x=np.random.normal(loc=50, scale=6,
                     size=20), y=50, paired=False, tail='greater',
                     correction='auto', confidence=0.95)['p-val'])
                     for _ in range(10000)]


# Check which p-values are less than alpha = 0.05 in the simulations

pvalue_less_alpha = [pvalue < 0.05 for pvalue in simulations]

# Find the mean of p-values that are less than alpha
# this gives the probability of type one error

prob_type_one_error = np.mean(pvalue_less_alpha)


prob_type_one_error
## 0.0503

As you can see the probability of type one error is approximately equal to the significance level which in our case is \(\alpha = 0.05\), so that means there is a 5% chance that we may reject the null hypothesis when it is true (false positive). So there is a 5% chance that we conclude that the mean temperature in May is greater than 50 degrees Fahrenheit when in reality it is not.

The probability of type one error is approximately equivalent to the significance level which is \(\alpha=0.01\). So we can interpret an alpha of 0.01 as a 1% chance that our results are due to chance rather than actual ozone concentration in June being less than 40 parts per billion.


5 Effect Size

When we conducted a t-test, we found that the average difference in temperature between May and July is statistically significant. However, we need to consider other factors that can make our results significant as well. Generally, when we increase the sample size, the p-value decreases which means that we are more likely to get a significant p-value even when the difference in outcomes between groups is negligible.

Therefore, even when the difference is statistically significant, it does not necessarily mean that it is big, important, or helpful in decision-making. It simply means you can be confident that there is a difference. To know if an observed difference is not only statistically significant but also important or meaningful, you will need to calculate its effect size. There are different ways to calculate effect size depending on the evaluation design you use. For example, when comparing two groups we typically use Cohen’s d. However, for regressions and correlations, the coefficient of determination \(R^2\) and Pearson correlation coefficient \(r\) effect size can be used respectively.


5.1 Cohen’s d

Cohen’s d is a common measure of effect size for t-test, and can be measured using the formula shown below:

\[\frac{M_{1}-M_{2}}{SD_{\text{pooled}}}\]

where,

  • \(M_1\) and \(M_2\) represent the mean value of the group 1 and 2, respectively. In our case, it is the mean temperature in May and July.

  • \(SD_{\text{pooled}}\) is a weighted average of standard deviations for two groups. It is used when we assume that the variance of both groups is the same.

Pooled standard deviation is used, when we assume that the variance of both groups is the same. We can carry out the formal test to see if variances between groups are significantly different or not:

  • Bartlett’s test: Compare the variances of k samples, where k can be more than two samples. The data must be normally distributed.

  • Levene’s test: Compare the variances of k samples, where k can be more than two samples. It’s an alternative to Bartlett’s test that is less sensitive to departures from normality.

Now, we will check if the variance between the temperature in May and July are significantly different or not.

# Create a new dataset and select temperature and month column

monthly_temp = airquality[['temp', 'month']]

# Filter out the temperature in May and July

temp_data = monthly_temp[(monthly_temp['month'] == 5) | 
                         (monthly_temp['month'] == 7)]

# Run the test where the dependent variable is temp and grouping variable is the month
# the method is Levene's (default) but can change to ‘bartlett’s

pg.homoscedasticity(data=temp_data, dv='temp', 
                    group='month', method='levene')
##                W      pval  equal_var
## levene  7.320055  0.008864      False

\(H_0:\) The variances of temperature in May and July are the same

\(H_a:\) The variances of temperature in May and July are different

Since the p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that there is a significant difference between the variances of both groups. Also, the output equal_val = False confirms that there is a significant difference between the variances of both groups. Therefore we will use unpooled SD for Cohen’s d calculation, which means we will set the argument/parameter paired = False when calculating the effect size.

# Calculate cohen's d using pg.compute_effsize()
# where x and y are the groups that you want to see the difference of
# parameter paired = False is used when we are assuming variance are not equal

effect_size_temp = pg.compute_effsize(x=temp_may, y=temp_july,
                   paired=False, eftype='Cohen')


round(effect_size_temp,3)
## -3.205


Cohen’s d is negative, which is expected since the mean temperature in May is less than the mean temperature in July. Since Cohen’s d is the magnitude of the mean difference between two groups, using absolute value/reversing the order is perfectly fine in this case. So, it is safe to say that the effect size is 3.205. However, in medical statistics, the sign of your Cohen’s d effect tells you the direction of the effect. For example, if M1 is your experimental group and M2 is your control group, a negative effect size indicates the effect decreases your mean, and a positive effect size indicates that the effect increases your mean.

Generally, a score of d = 1.0 means that the difference between the two groups is equal to one standard deviation. A score of d = 0.50 means that the difference between the two groups is equivalent to half of a standard deviation. The bigger the score, the bigger the difference between the groups and the bigger the effect. Here is a rough interpretation of cohen’s d values.



This means that if two group means don’t differ by 0.2 standard deviations or more, the difference is negligible, even if it is statistically significant. Note that, for a small sample size (< 50), Cohen’s d tends to over-inflate results. There exists a Hedge’s corrected version of Cohen’s d (Hedges and Olkin 1985), which provides a bias correction to Cohen’s d. Hedge’s g is also used when the sample sizes of the two groups are significantly different. The interpretation for both methods is the same.

# Create two samples from temperature_may and temperature_july variable
# to make sure the sample sizes are significantly different we will use sample()
# to make my results reproducible I will use the random_state parameter


sample_may  = temp_may.sample(n=5, random_state=1)    
sample_july = temp_july.sample(n=30, random_state=1)

# Use cohen and hedges effect size to see the difference in results

cohen = pg.compute_effsize(x=sample_may,y=sample_july,
                   paired=False, eftype='Cohen')

cohen
## -5.075239977361366
# Use cohen and hedges effect size to see the difference in results

hedges = pg.compute_effsize(x=sample_may, y=sample_july,
                   paired=False, eftype='hedges')

hedges
## -4.9590131076508

  1. Use help() function to find more information about pg.compute_effsize function.
# Finding information of compute_effsize function using help() function 

help(pg.compute_effsize)


There are potentially hundreds of different measures of the effect size and you will be required to use effect size depending on your statistical models. You can use pg.compute_effsize to compute the effect size of some of the statistical methods by specifying the parameter/argument eftype.

  • T-test: cohens is used for a larger sample size (greater than 50), hedges is used when the sample size of two groups are significantly different and the sample size is small (less than 50). There is a third type that is not included in this function but you can use researchpy.ttest() in the researchpy package to calculate the glass’s delta. Glass’s delta is used when two groups have a significantly different standard deviation, but this is used when you want to calculate the effect size between the experimental group and the control group.

  • Pearson correlation coefficient: choose the eftype = 'r'.

  • Odds ratio: when using pg.compute_effsize choose eftype = 'odds-ratio'.

  • One-way ANOVA test: choose eftype = 'eta-square'

  • Chi-squared test of independence or goodness-of-fit: we can use pg.chi2_independence to get the value for cramer.

  • Linear regression: coefficient of determination (\(R^2\)) is used as effect size (see Statistics for Data Science in Python course to learn about linear regression)


6 Probability of Type II error

So far we have learnt that increasing the sample size results in decreasing p-value, which means a significant p-value is likely to be found. However, decreasing the sample size means we might commit a Type II error.

Reminder: Type II occurs when a researcher does not reject a null hypothesis when in reality the null hypothesis was false.



The probability of making a type II error is called Beta \((\beta)\), and this is related to the power of the statistical test. Power is the probability of making a correct decision (to reject the null hypothesis) when the null hypothesis is false. It can also be described as the probability of avoiding a Type II error. Mathematically, we can write power as \(power = 1- \beta\).


6.1 Calculating power

In Python, we can use pingouin package to calculate the power of any test. I will use the example from the previous exercise, where I calculated the effect size to be 0.81 when I was conducting a two-sample independent t-test to see if the average ozone concentration in June is significantly different from the average ozone concentration in July.

# The pg.power_ttest2n function is used for two-sample t-test (unequal sample sizes)
# specify the effect size as d
# we want to calculate the power so set it to None
# specify the significance level to be 0.05
# and specify the alternative hypothesis which is 'two-sided' in our case

pg.power_ttest2n(nx=31, ny=30, d=0.81, power=None, alpha=0.05, tail='two-sided')
                  
## 0.8751093694181669

This gives us a power of 0.875. Hence the probability of committing Type II error (denoted by \(\beta\) ) is \(\beta = 1- \text{Power} = 1- 0.875 = 0.125\).

Let’s use the pg.power.power_ttest() function (which is used to calculate the power of two-sample, one-sample, independent and paired t-test for the equal sample size of both groups), to check the effect of sample size on power.

# Creating a sequence of sample sizes using power calculations for t-test
# where d is the medium effect size which is 0.5

sample_size = np.arange(start=10, stop=100, step=10) 

power_sample = pg.power_ttest(d=0.5, n=sample_size, alpha=0.05)

# Create a data frame that shows the sample size
# and corresponding power rounded to 2 decimal places

pd.DataFrame({'n': sample_size,
              'power': np.round(power_sample, 2)})  
##     n  power
## 0  10   0.19
## 1  20   0.34
## 2  30   0.48
## 3  40   0.60
## 4  50   0.70
## 5  60   0.78
## 6  70   0.84
## 7  80   0.88
## 8  90   0.92

This shows that increasing sample size increases the power of a test. Just like how \(\alpha\) is set by researchers (usually 0.05 or lower), Beta (\(\beta\)) is also commonly set at 0.2 or lower by researchers. Hence power ( 1-\(\beta\) ) is usually set to 0.8 or higher. Powers lower than 0.8 are not impossible, but would typically be considered too low for most areas of research. In reality, a researcher would want both Type I and Type II errors to be small. In terms of significance level and power this means we want a small significance level (close to 0) and a large power (close to 1).


6.1.1 Exercise

Exercise

We want to see if there’s an association between gender and education. We randomly sampled 629 people and saved the data in the Data folder. We want to see if there’s an association between gender and education. We randomly sampled 629 people and saved the data in the Data folder. We want to carry out a chi-square test of association to determine if there’s an association between these two variables while setting the significance level to be 0.01.

  1. Run the chi-square test using pg.chi2_independence() function to find the effect size. (Hint: use help(pg.chi2_independence)).
# Using pingouin.chi2_independence() function we get the expected, observed and stats

It depends on your data set, in our case we look at the Pearson method since we are testing if two variables are independent or not. The effect size is Cramer V which is 0.065 in our case.



  1. Calculate the power of the test and set effect size to w = 0.065. (Hint: use help(pg.power_chi2)).
# The dof is 6 as calculated in the previous question
# the effect size is w which is 0.65
# the sample size is n = 629 as given in the question
# alpha is 0.02 as given in the question

pg.power_chi2(dof=6, w=0.065, n=629, power=None, alpha=0.01)
## 0.06276846074453057

The power is 0.062 which is very low, so this is not a very powerful experiment.


  1. Calculate the probability of type II error of this test.

Since the probability of type II error is \(\beta\) and \(\text{power} = 1 - \beta\). Then, rearranging this formula give us \(\beta = 1- \text{power} = 1 - 0.062 = 0.938\). This is scarily high, we are saying the probability of us not rejecting a null hypothesis when in reality it is false is 0.938.


7 Sample Size

We have already seen how increasing the sample size increases the power of the test. This should intuitively make sense as well, as a large sample means that you have collected more information, which makes it easier to correctly reject the null hypothesis when you should. To ensure that your sample size is big enough, you will need to conduct a power analysis calculation.

Using the pingouin package we can conduct power analysis where we can specify any three quantities and get the fourth one since these four quantities are dependent on each other:

  • Sample Size
  • Effect Size
  • Significance level
  • Power

Let’s use the previous exercise (Chi-square test to find the association between gender and education) as an example where the power of the test was low (power = 0.062). Let’s run the same power test to calculate how many people I need to survey if I wish to achieve 90% power when the significance level is still 0.01 and the effect size is 0.065 that we calculated using pg.chi2_independence.

# Using pg.power_chi2() function because we want to calculate the sample size required,
# to achieve 90% power and w is the effect size as calculated previously
# the degrees of freedom is 6 and the significance level is 0.01

pg.power_chi2(dof=6, w=0.065, n=None, power=0.9, alpha=0.01)
## 5486.82335980266

We need to survey 5487 people to achieve 90% power when the significance level is 0.01. Always round estimates of required sample size up (even if the decimal place is below 0.5).

Usually, when conducting an experiment, we use conventional effect size. For example, how many students should we sample (to find the association between gender and education) to detect a medium effect, when power is 0.8, degrees of freedom is 6 and significance level is 0.01?

# Choose any value between 0.2 and 0.6 as shown in the last exercise table
# the power of the test is 0.8 and the degrees of freedom is 6

pg.power_chi2(dof=6, w=0.5, n=None, power=0.8, alpha=0.01)
## 75.48740710075526

We need to survey 76 students to detect a medium effect. Now we will look at the conventional effect size of the correlation test.



Suppose I want to conduct a one-sided correlation test to determine if there is a correlation between student’s absences and their final exam grades. I decide to carry out an experiment where I want to detect a large effect, with 90% power and 0.05 significance level. How many students do I need to carry out this experiment?

# Choose any value between 0.3 and 0.4 as shown in table above
# the power of test is 0.9
# tail = 'one-sided' because we are conducting one sided test

pg.power_corr(r=0.35, n=None, power=0.9, alpha=0.05, tail='one-sided' )
## 66.1621080271319

Hence, we need 67 students to detect a large effect, with 90% power and 0.05 significance level.

Let’s use the example from airqulity_data. If we are interested in conducting a two-sample independent t-test to see if the average temperature in May is significantly different from the average temperature in July, how many observations do I need to achieve 80% power when the significance level is still 0.05 and the effect size is medium?

# Use two-sample t-test (equal sample sizes) where medium cohen_d is between 0.5 to 0.8
# specify power which is 80% and the type since it is two-sample 
# specify the alternative hypothesis which is two-sided in our case

pg.power_ttest(d=0.5, n=None, power=0.8, alpha=0.05,
               contrast='two-samples', tail='two-sided')
## 63.76561137745679

We need 64 observations in total to achieve 80% power when the significance level is still 0.05.
